With Bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time the account holder, auditors, cash issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose another address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
With the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are available in the account books distributed throughout the network of public accounts.
The crucial step is to bring this new transaction into this book.
This is about a mathematical task that is started on computers, while the winner, who is a type of provisional central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computer "take" the new transaction and add a number before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is correct.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay twice (less than 10 minutes) with the same money for fraud, only one of the two transactions will be validated from the network and the other will remain unconnected, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
