As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the International Space Federation founded in 1951, and in fact PTA became a regular member in autumn 1956.
In the following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was elected vice president of the International Federation for Space Transport.
He had entered this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been involved in the development of the highly successful meteorological rockets (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rockets for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first started on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh a total of 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in 1959 started in the Błądów desert flight test with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another development level should already be able to do real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used to monitor altitudes.
In 1962, however, further development was introduced.
A successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B above 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C above 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude was 37 km for all three types.
In 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, whose first flight test began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a useful load of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
